So many people are fighting about this "origin" shit but truth is K-pop is not just about Hwasa or Jessie there are so many artists from each different genres and styles. But yes generally we can say K-pop is heavily influenced by black culture not just because Korean thought itâ€™s cool that they copied it. Itâ€™s more like because korean people actually found black culture is truly inspiring (possibly cuz of sad history) they tried to mix it and localise it. Truth is when black culture was introduced in Korea around 8-90s, a lot of people got shocked. Some loved it but a lot of people couldnâ€™t bare it. But still, tons of artists tried so hard to introduce this new world by mixing black culture and Korean culture and It took long enough for Korean people to get used to it but also for artists to find their way to mix those two completely different cultures. I donâ€™t think itâ€™s fair for some people to simply say K-pop just "copied" Black-Latin culture cuz if they actually just copied it without mixing it and localising it, this wouldnâ€™t have been accepted in Korea from the start cuz it was simply too different. Donâ€™t forget this being influenced heavily and copying is not the same. Think about Fried chicken. Itâ€™s clearly American but Korea adapted it and added new stuffs on it. 30years later, it evolved quite differently compare to American fried chicken that now it is called Korean(style) fried chicken. K-pop and K-culture fans need to accept that it is heavily influenced or partly originated by black culture but also black people need to stop seeing Asian like some kinda enemy who stole/copied black culture. Itâ€™s more like black soul touched and inspired soooo many people even though there is a huge cultural barrier. So letâ€™s just enjoy this and try to understand each other more instead of fighting and making enemies for nothing

I think the most amazing thing about JR is that they always rise to whatever is presented to them. Their normal style is so different from kpop choreo, so this to me is pretty damn amazing. Kpop songs are known to change melodies and grooves five to six times in one song, that's not the difficult part for them...the hard part is being able to tailor it to an artist you're not 100% familiar with.   You can see that  when Hwasa is presented, the other teams know her songs and dances, but Jam wasn't as familiar with her or her songs, or her dances...and yet they pulled out the best performance, in my opinion. They only get a few days to chorograph and fine tune, which is already insane...but to research the subject you have little previous knowedge about and STILL come up with a choreograph that fits the artists's style, the melodies AND the song lyrics (they don't speak Korean)is absolutely INSANE.   Not only that, but this needed to be tailored to a performer, it can't be TOO difficult, because they need to be able to sing and dance live, but it has to look like it is super hard to pull off and not be boring. Jam slayed, there were a couple of parts that I think needed to be tailored more to a singer...but those are details that are so easy to fix. BEBE a made an fantastic choreography, but they did not balance it out for a singer and that's a problem. Wolf'Lo made a choreography that was too dull and wasn't appealing to the eye, but kept the singer in mind. It's such a hard thing to balance.  I think 1 Million had the upperhand because of Lia's relationship to Hwasa, however they weren't as fun to watch as JR was.  Jam Republic really carried, and I love that for them.  This choreo really blows my mind.

I saw some comments saying this choreography isn't "that sensational." I don't know what they meant by that. But it seems to me that some people are so used to seeing only one way of dancing that they can't see anything else. Same goes for people who are saying "it's not sharp" or "the dance line is messy." Like, are you for real? Not all dances have to be sharp. I understand if it's just preference but it seems like some people really just want to put dance into one box. The world is wide. Get acquainted with different dance styles and genres. Widen your horizon. Do not be like a frog stuck in a well.

It is something not usual or common. It is something that would embodies the Chilin Song of Hwasa. Jamree is more on the international level while others is like the local level. So if Hwasa wants to bring her song to be notice worldwide go for Jamree but if she wants it to be easy for the local to imitate for tiktok then go for other dance group. I can't stop from watching this again and again! The other teams stick to the concept of "hey look at me, I'm the center" vibe that's why their performance is kinda off to me  because that's not a Hwasa vibe. In Hwasa's performances, every backup dancers compliments Hwasa's movement and they're blending perfectly that's why it's so addictive to watch (See Hip, Twit,  Maria, and I love my body).   The other teams just focused on how to make the center stand out from the rest that it becomes messy and movements become stiff and jumbled from the eyes of other viewers.  On the other hand, Jam Republic did the opposite. Kirsten, the center, did not stand out by using "red" concept, instead, use "black" to compliment the "white" of her supposed "back up dancer" co-members. It's striking, and highlights every detail of their movements. They also got the center - back up dancer interaction WHICH IS A GOOSEBUMPS for me because it is very VERY MUCH HWASA. In addition to that, Kirsten's intro and ending pose are both on point!!! They embodied the groovy, sexy, and swag Hwasa all throughout the song by means of maximizing the stage and every sequence of their choreo.   If they (just a what if) will not win this mission, then I think there's something REALLY wrong on swf2 because there are only two reason why a video becomes trending WORLDWIDE: either it is THAT BAD or it is THAT GOOD.   Overall, as one of the Momoos who grew up seeing how Hwasa perform, I really appreaciate and love this choreo among the rest.

If I were to choose the parts I love from each crews, I would choose Mannequeen on the intro up to 'mi casa su casa' , ladybounce on 1st verse/pre chorus, combination of bebe and wolf lo (that dipping sauce move) on 1st chorus, jam republic on refrain/pre chorus 2 that 'trash' part , wolf lo on that 'shimmy shimy Yaya' part, 1 million/jam republic (fanning move) on 2nd chorus,  I made a compilation of my favorite parts of all crews for this song: https://youtu.be/KLcv9fbEKtE?si=jfsU0SDAcRZl4hNU I just can't pick one so I chose the ones that made an impression on me of each crew ğŸ˜Š
The performance is so eye-catching throughout. Not a single second is wasted and each new scene is so exciting and different,  leaving me trying to guess what they'll do next. It just feels so genuine, like they're dancing from pure emotion (judging by their facial expressions and bold movements). The moves are also very clear and have a very big focus on delivery. Watching Jam Republic really made me appreciate dance so much as an art ğŸ‡ğŸ’—

ì§„ì‹¬ ë¹„ìš˜ì„¸ ê°™ì•„ìš”!!!!!
If you're wondering why you keep replaying this, it's because it's memorable from start to finish. Compared to other teams, Jam Republic don't have a cliche repetitive dance sequence for the chorus so you HAVE to watch it from beginning to end, bloody captivating. This piece tells a superb story without compromising the lead with flashy movements, highlighting her amazingly. Perfect sequence that doesn't look back and let's the audience enjoy comfortably with no expectations of repeating moves despite having a song with a catchy chorus and a consistent beat with minimal variance.   Teamwork was stellar. Each dancer was engaged from the start, no one stops to wait for the next move or leave the stage/camera's view unengaged. Even though such transitions/pauses to a set aren't meant to be shown, viewers still spot them, and often times, those who leave the stage or pause to wait, stand out even more.    Sweatless performance that gave 100%. Obvious show stealer.  *Edit: Yes! song's on Spotify now!

If Hwasa is making a comeback in a new genre, then the timing seems perfect for her to challenge herself. If not, Jam Republic or One Million would probably be the best fit for Hwasa's style and would suit her well. Bebe = edgy and trendy / Jam Republic = sophisticated and powerful / One Million = smooth and charismatic. However, ultimately, Jam Republic's choreography would be perfect for Hwasa to perform live as it allows the artist to have minimal movement while still taking all the spotlight, with the dancers providing strong support. It seems like choreography that is well-suited for an artist to take the stage. Well done with the choreography.
